'''Nico Cédric Schlotterbeck''' ({{IPA|de|ˈniːko ˈʃlɔtɐˌbɛk}}; born 1 December 1999) is a German professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays primarily as a [[centre-back]] for {{German football updater|BoDortmu}} club [[Borussia Dortmund]] and the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]]. He is known for his aerial ability, speed, strength and aggressive tackling.<ref name="worldfootball">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe415412/nico-schlotterbeck/ |title=Nico Schlotterbeck |website=WorldFootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL |access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title= "Mein Bruder hat mir einiges berichtet": Union holt Nico Schlotterbeck | url = https://www.kicker.de/_mein_bruder_hat_mir_einiges_berichtet_union_holt_nico_schlotterbeck-780842/artikel | date = 31 July 2020 |access-date= 26 March 2022|website=kicker|language=de}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Schlotterbeck began his club career together with his older brother [[Keven Schlotterbeck|Keven]] in his home district [[Rems-Murr]] at ''SG Weinstadt''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nico Schlotterbeck: Freiburgs Verteidiger und der Traum vom "besten Verein" |url=https://www.swr.de/sport/fussball/sc-freiburg/artikel-sc-freiburg-spieler-der-vorrunde-nico-schlotterbeck-100.html |website=swr.de |access-date=9 January 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220106082529/https://www.swr.de/sport/fussball/sc-freiburg/artikel-sc-freiburg-spieler-der-vorrunde-nico-schlotterbeck-100.html |archive-date=6 January 2022 |language=German |date=22 December 2021}}</ref> Both his father and uncle [[Niels Schlotterbeck]] used to play football themselves, although the former had to end his career early at the age of 19 due to illness.<ref name="BVB Story">{{cite web |title=Nico Schlotterbeck: Wie alles begann |url=https://www.bvb.de/de/de/aktuelles/news/news.html/nico-schlotterbeck-wie-alles-begann.html |website=bvb.de |access-date=9 January 2026 |language=German}}</ref> During trial training sessions, the brothers Nico and Keven, who grew up in the district [[Beutelsbach]] in [[Weinstadt]], were accepted into the academy of [[Stuttgart Kickers]]. Their friend [[Antonios Papadopoulos (footballer)|Antonios Papadopoulos]], also born in 1999, was accepted along with them.<ref name="BVB Story" /> Papadopoulos and Schlotterbeck played together in Stuttgart until the Under-15s and also faced teams such as [[AFC Ajax|Ajax Amsterdam]] and [[Juventus FC]] in junior tournaments.<ref name="BVB Story" /><ref name= "SWR Story II">{{cite web |author1=Michael Richmann |title=Nico Schlotterbeck - Durchstarter mit langem Anlauf |url=https://www.swr.de/sport/fussball/sc-freiburg/artikel-sc-freiburg-nico-schlotterbeck-100.html |website=swr.de |access-date=9 January 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220106082538/https://www.swr.de/sport/fussball/sc-freiburg/artikel-sc-freiburg-nico-schlotterbeck-100.html |archive-date=6 January 2022 |language=German |date=30 October 2021}}</ref> After a year at [[VfR Aalen]], which uncle Niels Schlotterbeck described as a ‘step backwards’,<ref name="SWR Story II" /> things started looking up again for the youngster in 2015 when he was accepted into the Under-17s team of [[Karlsruher SC]].
Under the coach [[Lukas Kwasniok]] Schlotterbeck played as centre-back in that team and was together with [[Tim Kircher]] for example part of the defense unit which would later go on to play professionally at the KSC.<ref>{{cite web |website=sueddeutsche.de |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/sport/fussball-schlotterbeck-gemerkt-dass-stuermer-angst-vor-mir-haben-dpa.urn-newsml-dpa-com-20090101-220820-99-455808 |title=Schlotterbeck: Gemerkt, dass Stürmer Angst vor mir haben |trans-title=Schlotterbeck: Realized that strikers were afraid of me|date=2022-08-20 |access-date=2022-08-20}}</ref> As part of the Under-17s  Schlotterbeck finished in the upper half of the league standings and scored two goals. Due to his rough playing style he was at risk for being suspended for too many yellow cards a second time after already receiving a first suspension during that season. At only 16 years old he was then called up into the Under-19 squad of the Karlsruher SC where he started, like in the previous Under-17s, as a regular. His first season in the Under-19 team was simultaneously his last at Karlsruhe. During that year he sometimes played midfield but overall he remained a steady part of the teams defense. Although playing as centre-back he still managed to score 7 goals, three of which were headers and provide one assist.

===SC Freiburg===
====Professional debut====
Together with his brother Keven, Schlotterbeck joined the Bundesliga side coached by [[Christian Streich]] in the summer of 2018. Both took part in the pre-season training and continued to train regularly with the first team afterwards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 June 2019 |title=Keven und Nico Schlotterbeck verlängern {{!}} SC Freiburg |url=https://www.scfreiburg.com/node/24364 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608201106/https://www.scfreiburg.com/node/24364 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2019-06-08 |access-date=10 January 2026 |website=www.scfreiburg.com |language=de}}</ref> Schlotterbeck debuted for [[SC Freiburg]] on 9 March 2019, coming on as a half-time substitute for [[Philipp Lienhart]] in the 2–1 home win against [[Hertha BSC]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/freiburg-gegen-hertha-2019-bundesliga-4243487/analyse |title=Herthas Unglücksrabe heißt Ibisevic |trans-title=Hertha's misfortune is called Ibišević |website=[[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]] |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker-sportmagazin]] |date=9 March 2019 |access-date=16 March 2019 |language=German}}</ref> The two brothers started as central defenders on matchday 29 in a 2–1 away defeat in [[SV Werder Bremen|Bremen]], playing the full match alongside [[Dominique Heintz]]. They also played together frequently in the [[Regionalliga Südwest]], where Nico scored two goals. While Keven spent the 2019−20 season on loan at newly promoted [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]], Streich focused on further integrating Nico into the first-team squad. Nico played the full 90 minutes in each of the first three league matches. In the 3–0 victory over [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]], he was rated by kicker as Freiburg’s second-best player in terms of average match ratings, behind goalkeeper [[Alexander Schwolow]] and alongside [[Luca Waldschmidt]] and [[Lucas Höler]].<ref name="einsätze1920">[https://www.kicker.de/nico-schlotterbeck/spieler-einsaetze/bundesliga/2019-20/sc-freiburg ''Spielereinsätze 2019/20''], kicker.de, accessed on 10 January 2026</ref> After a bad performance in Freiburg’s 2–1 loss against [[1. FC Köln|1.FC Köln]] on matchday 3 he was relegated to being a substitute in the following games.<ref name="einsätze1920"/> For the remainder of the season, he only started one more game and was substituted on a few times, while also playing for the second team in the [[Regionalliga|fourth division]]. Nevertheless, he received a call-up for [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany’s under-21’s]].

In his final match for Freiburg in 2022, the club lost the [[2022 DFB-Pokal Final|DFB-Pokal Final]] on penalties but Schlotterbeck was awarded the man of the match.<ref>{{Cite web |last=GmbH |first=Perform Media Deutschland |date=22 May 2022 |title=SC Freiburg – RB Leipzig, Stimmen zum DFB-Pokalfinale: Man darf den alten Trainer nicht schlecht machen |url=https://www.spox.com/de/sport/fussball/dfbpokal/saison-2021-2022/finale/sc-freiburg-rb-leipzig/finale-stimmen-zum-leipziger-pokalsieg-tedesco-lobt-marsch.html |access-date=31 May 2022 |website=www.spox.com |language=de}}</ref>

====Loan to Union Berlin====
With his brother Keven returning from loan at [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]], they were in need of a new centre-back. They agreed a deal with Freiburg for a loan of Nico Schlotterbeck for the [[2020–21 Bundesliga|2020–2021]] season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Union leiht Nico Schlotterbeck |url=https://www.fc-union-berlin.de/de/union-live/news/profis/Union-leiht-Nico-Schlotterbeck--20176J/ |access-date=15 January 2026 |date=31 July 2020}}</ref> He lived in [[Köpenick]], in close proximity to his new club’s environment and started three of first four games of the season before being sidelined by a thigh injury until the second half of the season. Upon his return he proved to be a reliable centre-back, pushing [[Florian Hübner]] to the bench. On matchday 22, he triumphed after a 1–0 win over his main club SC Freiburg where his brother Keven still played. Nico had previously missed the first leg due to an injury. At the end of the season, Union Berlin ranked fourth in fewest goals conceded (champions [[FC Bayern Munich|FC Bayern München]] were fifth). As seventh in the table they earned the right to participate in the qualifiers for the newly introduced [[UEFA Conference League|UEFA Europa Conference League]], thanks to the victory of runners-up [[Borussia Dortmund]] in the [[2020–21 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]]. Schlotterbeck was voted into the German soccer rankings for the first time at the end of the season, where he finished 18th in the national class. That placed him ahead of [[Arminia Bielefeld|Bielefeld]]'s [[Amos Pieper]] and behind [[Hertha BSC]]'s [[Niklas Stark]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Summer 2021 rankings: Center backs |url=https://www.kicker.de/bundesliga-sommer-2021/innenverteidiger/rangliste |website=kicker.de |access-date=14 January 2026}}</ref>

===Borussia Dortmund===
On 2 May 2022, [[Borussia Dortmund]] announced the signing of Schlotterbeck on a five-year deal, starting from the 2022–23 season.<ref>{{cite web | title = BVB signs Nico Schlottbeck | url = https://www.bvb.de/eng/News/Overview/BVB-sign-Nico-Schlotterbeck| publisher=Borussia Dortmund | date=2 May 2022 | access-date=2 May 2022}}</ref> He joined for a reported €25 million transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Johnson |first=Paul |date=3 May 2022 |title=Borussia Dortmund Sign Nico Schlotterbeck from Freiburg for €25m |url=https://www.fearthewall.com/2022/5/3/23054928/borussia-dortmund-sign-nico-schlotterbeck-from-freiburg-for-25m-niklas-sule-bayern-munich-bundesliga |access-date=3 May 2022 |website=[[SB Nation]]}}</ref> He would almost win the league with Dortmund in his first season, but merely became runners-up due to goal difference. In the 2023–24 season, he achieved the highest [[Sliding tackle|tackling]] success rate in the [[2023–24 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] at 71%, in addition to winning possession over 240 times, he also played a crucial role in his club's qualification to the [[2024 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]] alongside fellow centre-back [[Mats Hummels]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tribuna.com/de/news/dortmund-2024-05-14-statistik-beweist-tacklingmonster-schlotterbeck-wurde-in-den-emkader-absolut-verdient-ber/ |title=Statistik beweist: Tackling-Monster Schlotterbeck wurde in den EM-Kader absolut verdient berufen! |publisher=Tribuna.com |language=de |date=14 May 2024 }}</ref>

In the 2024–25 season, he earned a place in the Bundesliga Team of the Season, even though he suffered an injury toward the end of the campaign, which also caused him to miss the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/schlotterbeck-kuendigt-rueckzug-aus-der-oeffentlichkeit-an-fuer-meinen-kopf-1109499/artikel |title=Schlotterbeck kündigt Rückzug aus der Öffentlichkeit an: "Für meinen Kopf" |publisher=Kicker |language=de |date=8 April 2025 }}</ref> On 10 April 2026, he extended his contract with the club until 2031.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bvb.de/de/en/news/news-overview/news.html/2026/4/10/Borussia-Dortmund-extends-contract-with-Nico-Schlotterbeck.html |title=Borussia Dortmund extends contract with Nico Schlotterbeck |publisher=Borussia Dortmund |date=10 April 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
Schlotterbeck got his debut call-up to the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]] under coach [[Hansi Flick]] for [[FIFA World Cup qualification]] in September 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/bundestrainer-flick-beruft-drei-neulinge-und-fuenf-rueckkehrer-231201/
|title=Bundestrainer Flick beruft drei Neulinge und fünf Rückkehrer |publisher=dfb.de |date=27 August 2021 |access-date=6 September 2021}}</ref> He made his debut against Israel in a friendly on 27 March 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Flick on Schlotterbeck's Germany debut: "Hopefully, it will be a good lesson for him" |url=https://bulinews.com/news/12042/flick-schlotterbecks-germany-debut-hopefully-will-a-good-lesson-for-him |access-date=31 May 2022 |website=Bulinews |date=27 March 2022 |language=en}}</ref> Later that year, on 10 November, he was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/flick-beruft-moukoko-fuellkrug-und-goetze-in-wm-kader-245974/ |title=Flick beruft Moukoko, Füllkrug und Götze in WM-Kader |trans-title=Flick names Moukoko, Füllkrug and Götze to World Cup squad |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=10 November 2022 |access-date=10 November 2022 |language=de}}</ref>

Schlotterbeck was named in Germany's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://olympics.com/en/news/uefa-euro-2024-all-squads-and-players-full-list|title=UEFA Euro 2024: All squads and players full list|date=7 June 2024|access-date=7 June 2024|website=Olympics.com}}</ref>

On 21 May 2026, he was selected in Germany’s 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/news/bundestrainer-nagelsmann-gibt-wm-kader-bekannt|title=Bundestrainer Nagelsmann gibt WM-Kader bekannt|publisher=[[German Football Association]]|language=de|date=21 May 2026|access-date=21 May 2026}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Schlotterbeck is the nephew of former professional footballer [[Niels Schlotterbeck]], who played for Freiburg.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scfreiburg.com/squad/keven-schlotterbeck |title=Keven Schlotterbeck |website=scfreiburg.com |publisher=[[SC Freiburg]] |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=German |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924190702/https://www.scfreiburg.com/squad/keven-schlotterbeck |archive-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> His older brother, [[Keven Schlotterbeck|Keven]], is a professional footballer who plays for Bavarian side [[FC Augsburg]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Frahm |first=Daniela |url=https://www.kicker.de/sc-mit-einem-schlotterbeck---oder-auch-mit-zwei-744575/artikel |title=SC mit einem Schlotterbeck – oder auch mit zwei |trans-title=SC with a Schlotterbeck – or with two |website=[[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]] |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker-sportmagazin]] |date=14 March 2019 |access-date=16 March 2019 |language=German}}</ref> Schlotterbeck's cousin, Sandrine, appeared on the seventh series of the German edition of [[Love Island (German TV series)|''Love Island'']] in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Möller |first=Domescu |title="Love Island"-Kandidatin Sandrine ist gleich mit zwei Ex-Unionern verwandt – raten Sie mal mit wem! |url=https://www.berliner-kurier.de/show/love-island/love-island-diese-reality-tv-kandidatin-ist-gleich-mit-zwei-ex-unionern-verwandt-li.217335 |access-date=31 May 2022 |website=Berliner Kurier |date=23 March 2022 |language=de-DE}}</ref>

